<FIRST>r i BC-Burma-Quake     10-01 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Burma-Quake,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits Burma, Northern Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second strong earthquake in as many
days struck eastern Burma near the Thai border early Sunday, the
meteorological department said, shaking tall buildings in the Thai
capital hundreds of miles away.
   The quake, measuring 6.0 on the Richter scale, was centered
about 12 miles west of the northern Thai province of Chiang Mai, an
official said on condition of anonymity.
   There were no immediate reports of casualties.
   Tremors could be felt as far away as Bangkok, about 360 miles to
the south. Tall buildings in the capital shook noticeably.
   Another earthquake measuring 5.0 on the Richter scale hit the
same area Saturday, the official said.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in populated
areas.
</TEXT>
