<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 0710EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Refugees     10-01 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Refugees,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Fleeing Via Czechoslovakia and Poland To Number About
7,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special trains from Czechoslovakia and
Poland rumbled through the night, carrying thousands of East German
refugees to West Germany on Sunday.
   Officials said the total number of refugees on their way would
be around 7,000, far more than originally expected. There were
reports the exodus sparked even more East Germans to try to flee
via Prague, Czechoslovakia.
   An agreement between West Germany and Communist East Berlin
cleared the way for the exodus of thousands of East Germans who had
been holed up in Bonn's embassies in Prague and Warsaw, the Polish
capital.
   Hungary's decision last month to open the floodgates to East
German refugees already has brought more than 24,000 people to West
Germany via Austria.
   Three trains arrived from Prague by 10:30 a.m. (5:30 a.m. EDT),
bringing the total from the first three trains to more than 3,000
people. Three more trains were expected during the course of the
day from Prague, carrying about 1,000 people each.
   A train carrying more than 800 East German refugees from Warsaw
was expected to reach West Germany at the Helmstedt border crossing
late Sunday afternoon.
   Earlier reports said the number of refugees expected from Prague
was about 3,500, although officials in Hof said that figure did not
include many of the children accompanying their parents.
   In addition, Bavarian border police spokesman Klaus Papenfuss
said East Germans who had not even been at the embassies in either
city reportedly went directly to the railroad stations to board the
special trains.
   West German officials in Prague said about 100 more East Germans
sought refuge at the embassy after the compound was cleared early
Sunday. Witnesses also said scores of East Germans were rushing to
Czechoslovakia in cars after learning of the decision to allow the
others to leave.
   Police ringed off the West German Embassy in Prague Sunday
morning to thwart any more would-be escapees.
</TEXT>
