<FIRST>r a BC-Marcos     10-01 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Marcos,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos' Son Says Father's Death Marks End of an Era</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of the late Philippine President
Ferdinand Marcos vowed his family would some day return from exile,
and that his father would be buried in his homeland.
   Ferdinand ``Bong Bong'' Marcos Jr. defended his father's memory
in a speech Saturday to the United Filipino Council of Hawaii,
saying his autocratic rule was needed to keep peace in his country.
   ``It really is a period of mourning, not a time for politicking
and speeches,'' the 32-year-old son said. ``But this is the end of
an era, and as one chapter closes, another opens, and I find myself
facing the awesome responsibility of trying to fill my father's
shoes.''
   The elder Marcos died Thursday in a Honolulu hospital of heart
failure at age 72.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino, who took Marcos' place when
the strongman fled to Hawaii after a disputed election in 1986, has
refused to allow Marcos' remains to be returned for burial for fear
the return would cause unrest.
   The younger Marcos repeated a promise made earlier by the former
first lady, Imelda Marcos, that the family would continue to work
for the return of his father's remains.
   ``If it takes years, he will be brought home,'' the son said.
   He also promised the Marcos family would return to the
Philippines.
   ``We are not going back to pursue any personal vengeance,''
Marcos said. ``We are going back to try and help get the
Philippines out of the troubles that it has now.''
   Marcos didn't give specifics.
   After the speech, Marcos declined to rule out the possibility of
running for office in the Philippines, but said he didn't forsee it
happening soon.
   During the elder Marcos 20-year rule, the son said, he ``took a
feudalistic, divided nation and made it strong. He built the
economy and gave Filipinos a national identity that they could be
proud of and fight and die for.''
</TEXT>
