<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     10-01 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Backers Rally; President Says She'll Heed Court Ruling on
Body Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 people loyal to Ferdinand
Marcos marched through the capital on Sunday and demanded that
President Corazon Aquino allow the late leader's body to be buried
in his homeland.
   Mrs. Aquino said Sunday she will follow any Supreme Court order
to allow the return of Marcos' body, but was confident the justices
would support her ban.
   Marcos died Thursday in Honolulu at age 72. Mrs. Aquino banned
the return of his body on grounds it might cause civil disorder and
asked the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration to prevent any
aircraft from violating her order.
   Attorneys for Marcos said they would file a motion Monday asking
the Supreme Court to reconsider its Sept. 15 decision dismissing a
petition to allow Marcos to come home.
   Marcos had lived in exile in Hawaii since he was ousted in a
popular uprising three years ago that propelled Mrs. Aquino to
power.
   In an 8-7 vote, the court agreed with Mrs. Aquino that the
former president's return ``poses a serious threat to national
interest.''
   Marcos' lawyers hope the justices will reconsider now that the
former president is dead and since the vote on the first
consideration was so close.
   ``I will certainly respect the decision of the Supreme Court,''
Mrs. Aquino said in her weekly nationwide radio program Sunday.
``And I believe they can arrive at the best decision possible.''
   Mrs. Aquino said she believed she could explain to the justices
``what I really want to achieve'' for the welfare of the country.
She said the ban would be continually reviewed but ``at this time
there is really nothing so far to make me change my original
decision, which is not to allow the return of President Marcos'
body.''
   In a statement Sunday, opposition groups said they would
``exhaust all peaceful and legal means'' to bring his body home.
   The statement by the New Society Movement and the Nacionalista
Party of Vice President Salvador Laurel claimed public opinion
favored the burial of the former president ``in the land of his
birth.''
   Following a meeting at the presidential palace Saturday, Sen.
Neptali Gonzales said Mrs. Aquino ordered the ban after receiving
unspecified intelligence information ``of a national security
nature.'' Gonzales refused to elaborate.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, is barred from leaving the United States
because she has been indicted on racketeering charges in the
alleged embezzlement of Philippine government money. She is to go
on trial in New York in March.
   Despite government fears of unrest, the few pro-Marcos rallies
held since his death have been peaceful.
   In Sunday's march, about 1,000 loyalists carried banners in a
downtown park urging Mrs. Aquino to reconsider the ban. They later
marched to Camp Crame, headquarters of the Philippine Constabulary,
where they held a vigil.
   Prayer vigils were held at the Marcos family home in suburban
San Juan and at the home where he grew up in Batac in Ilocos Norte
province, 250 miles north of Manila.
   Batac Mayor Jesus Nalupta said Marcos supporters had decided on
peaceful protests so as not to give the government another excuse
for banning the burial.
</TEXT>
