<FIRST>r a AM-Poll-Method     10-01 0970</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Method,1011</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll on Drugs Reached 1,071 Nationwide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews Sept. 14-24 with 1,071 adults in the
continental United States. Phone numbers were selected randomly and
interviews were conducted with the adult who had the most recent
birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that 19 of
20 times its findings should be within 3 points of the result if
every adult American were asked the same questions. The error
margin is larger for subgroups.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions in this
poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. What do you think is the most important problem facing this
country today? Drugs: 61 percent. Federal deficit: 5 percent.
Economy: 3 percent. Environment: 3 percent. Homelessnes: 3 percent.
Other answers: 22 percent. Don't know or no answer: 2 percent.
   2. (If ``drugs'') Do you think that problem will get better or
worse in the next 10 years, or stay about the same? Better: 36.
Worse: 44. Same: 14. DK-NA: 5.
   3. Please tell me if each of the following is objectionable to
you, or not:
   a. Someone growing marijuana for their own use and smoking it at
home. Objectionable: 73. Not objectionable: 26. DK-NA: 1.
   b. Someone buying marijuana and smoking it at home.
Objectionable: 83. Not objectionable: 16. DK-NA: 2.
   c. Someone selling marijuana. Objectionable: 92. Not
objectionable: 6. DK-NA: 1.
   d. Someone buying cocaine and using it at home. Objectionable:
96. Not objectionable: 4. DK-NA: 1.
   e. Someone selling cocaine. Objectionable: 97. Not
objectionable: 3. DK-NA: 1.
   4. In your opinion, how much of a problem is illegal drug use in
your neighborhood _ very serious, somewhat serious, not too serious
or not at all serious? Very: 14. Somewhat: 26. Not too: 31. Not at
all: 25. DK-NA: 5.
   5a. Do you personally know anyone who you believe uses cocaine
or crack? Yes: 31. No: 67. DK-NA: 2.
   b. (If yes) Have you ever tried to get them to stop, or not?
Yes: 56. No: 44. DK-NA: 1.
   c. (If yes to 5a) Do you personally know anyone who you believe
is addicted to cocaine or crack? Yes: 53. No: 42. DK-NA: 5.
   6. If an occasional drug user is caught with illegal drugs in
his or her car ...
   a. should the car be taken away as part of the penalty? Yes: 63.
No: 29. DK-NA: 8.
   b. should his or her driver's license be suspended as part of
the penalty? Yes: 82. No: 14. DK-NA: 5.
   7. Should occasional drug users be sent to military-style boot
camps as punishment, or not? Yes: 47. No: 42. DK-NA: 12.
   8. If a pupil is caught with drugs at school, should the school
....
   a. notify the parents? Yes: 99. No: 1.
   b. notify the police? Yes: 78. No: 15. DK-NA: 8.
   c. suspend the pupil from classes? Yes: 60. No: 31. DK-NA: 9.
   d. expel the pupil from school? Yes: 26. No: 61. DK-NA: 13.
   9. Do you think the federal government can or cannot
significantly reduce the use of illegal drugs in this country? Can:
65. Cannot: 29. DK-NA: 6.
   10. Do you think the Bush administration is making a serious
effort to combat illegal drug use, or not? Yes: 74. No: 20. DK-NA:
6.
   11a. Which of these do you think will do the most to reduce the
use of illegal drugs _ cracking down on drug producers overseas, on
drug dealers in this country, or on drug users in this country?
Producers: 23. Dealers: 27. Users: 23. Equal: 21. None: 3. DK-NA: 2.
   b. And which of these do you think will do more to reduce the
use of illegal drugs _ punishing drug users, or putting them into
drug treatment programs? Punish: 28. Treat: 60. DK-NA: 12.
   12. To pay for federal anti-drug programs, which would you
prefer _ taking money away from other programs, or raising taxes?
Taking: 47. Raising: 34. DK-NA: 19.
   13. A federal anti-drug effort has been proposed costing $7.9
billion in the next fiscal year _ an increase of $2 billion over
this year. Do you think that's too much money, not enough, or about
the right amount of money? Too much: 13. Not enough: 24. Right: 39.
DK-NA: 24.
   14. To pay for a bigger federal anti-drug program, would you
support or oppose:
   a. Higher federal taxes on alcoholic beverages? Support: 78.
Oppose: 20. DK-NA: 3.
   b. Higher federal taxes on cigarettes? Support: 75. Oppose: 23.
DK-NA: 2.
   c. A 1 percent increase in federal personal income taxes?
Support: 43. Oppose: 53. DK-NA: 4.
   d. A 1 percent increase in federal corporate income taxes?
Support: 70. Oppose: 25. DK-NA: 5.
   15. Please tell me whether you think each of these items will or
will not reduce illegal drug use in this country:
   a. Building more federal prison cells for drug offenders. Will:
39. Will not: 57. DK-NA: 4.
   b. Spending more federal money on drug treatment programs. Will:
80. Will not: 17. DK-NA: 3.
   c. Spending more federal money on drug education in schools.
Will: 91. Will not: 7. DK-NA: 2.
   d. Spending more federal money on military and law enforcement
aid to the main cocaine exporting countries of Colombia, Bolivia
and Peru. Will: 65. Will not: 26. DK-NA: 9.
   16. Should President Bush order the United States armed forces
to patrol the nation's borders for drug smugglers? Yes: 82. No: 14.
DK-NA: 4.
   17. Should Bush order the United States armed forces to conduct
military strikes against illegal drug operations in foreign
countries? Yes: 43. No: 46. DK-NA: 11.
</TEXT>
