<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Yonkers     10-01 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Yonkers,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court To Review Fines Against Yonkers Councilmen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Scotus-Conservatives Bjt ^By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the first cases to be argued before the
Supreme Court in the new term centers on whether a federal judge
acted within his authority by fining and threatening to jail four
city councilmen who defied his desegregation order.
   The Yonkers, N.Y., councilmen maintain that the judge tried to
intimidate them into voting for a plan they opposed, thereby
violating their legislative immunity or the right to vote as they
choose without fear of punishment by the courts.
   The federal government maintains the councilmen were in contempt
of a court order, and that legislative immunity is not a license to
disobey the law.
   The case, to be argued Monday, is an outgrowth of an
acrimonious, nine-year battle in which the federal government has
been trying to induce Yonkers _ the state's fourth-largest city,
just north of New York City _ to build low-income housing in white
neighborhoods. The housing has not yet been built as city leaders
argue over sites and money.
   The original case was filed by the Justice Department in 1980.
Five years later, U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand found Yonkers
had for 40 years deliberately concentrated virtually all its
subsidized housing in the southwest quadrant to keep blacks
separate from whites. Sand ordered the city to build 200 units of
public housing in white neighborhoods in 1988 and to plan for 600
more.
   But the city defaulted and unsuccessfully appealed. Sand then
ordered Yonkers to adopt a package of financial incentives designed
to attract the low- and moderate-income housing or face fines
starting at $100 a day and doubling each day until they reached $1
million daily.
   In August 1988, the council voted 4-3 against the package. The
four dissident councilmen _ Nicholas V. Longo, Edward J. Fagan Jr.,
Peter Chema and Vice Mayor Henry Spallone _ were held in contempt,
fined $500 a day and threatened with jail for refusing to vote for
desegregation plan.
   Facing bankruptcy, Yonkers prepared to lay off hundreds of
employees and asked the Supreme Court to overturn the fines. The
court refused, and Yonkers paid $819,000 before Chema and Longo
switched their votes and the plan passed, 5-2.
   Each councilman paid $3,500 in fines. Spallone and Fagan
remained defiant, but their punishment has been stayed pending
appeal.
   In asking the Supreme Court to hear Spallone's case, his lawyers
argued the lower courts had ``done violence'' to the doctrine of
legislative immunity.
   ``Whether one agrees or disagrees with any legislator's apparent
political agenda, tactics or motive, the doctrine must remain
inviolate,'' they wrote. ``Inquiry into motives for legislative
action is precisely one of the evils which the doctrine seeks to
prevent.''
   But the United States, in its brief, argued that the city
government had already agreed to the desegregation order when the
councilmen voted against the plan.
   ``The (Supreme) Court has never considered the common law
doctrine of legislative immunity as a license to disobey federal
court orders,'' the government argued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
