<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Opera     10-01 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenor Richard Leech Makes Met Debut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Opera's first performance of
``La Boheme'' this season had just one thing going for it, but that
turned out to be a lot.
   Richard Leech, a young American tenor of outstanding promise,
made his debut Saturday afternoon in the role of Rodolfo, the
Bohemian writer whose love affair with the fatally ill Mimi forms
the slender plot of Puccini's masterpiece.
   Leech justified the excitement he has stirred in Chicago, Berlin
and other operatic centers. Though only 32, he used his warm,
medium-size voice with the ease and grace of a veteran, and he came
closer to looking the part than most tenors the Met engages. The
audience gave him a standing ovation at the final curtain.
   The rest of the performance wasn't much to cheer about.
   As Mimi, the Korean-born soprano Hei-Kyung Hong was a bit out of
her league, her lovely but small voice unable to bloom and soar
over the orchestra at climactic moments. Soprano Sona Ghazarian's
rough tones failed to captivate during her big moment, Musetta's
Waltz Song. Baritone Brian Schexnayder was a stalwart but
small-scale Marcello, the hero's best friend.
   Conductor Donato Renzetti, also making his Met debut, gave an
account of the score that was more plodding than impassioned. One
of Puccini's most ingenious touches is the way he swiftly brings
the curtain down after Mimi dies; on Saturday, the final measures
seemed to last forever.
   As much a problem as ever were the gargantuan sets by Franco
Zeffirelli, which often make it hard for the singers to be heard or
noticed. What should be a warm, intimate attic setting for the
first and fourth acts is turned into a Parisian skyline, with the
garret pushed back behind rooftops and chimneys. The split-level
set for the second-act cafe scene is so elaborate and has so many
people milling about that it's hard to concentrate on the action.
   Zeffirelli has created similarly bloated spectacles in recent
seasons for two other Puccini operas. In ``Turandot,'' the glitz
seemed to fit the grandiose music and action; but in ``Tosca,'' the
love story was again pushed aside to make room for stage gimmickry.
   Two of this season's five new productions _ Verdi's ``La
Traviata'' and Mozart's ``Don Giovanni'' _ have been put in his
hands, apparently on the theory that Zeffirelli sets will bring in
an audience even if the singing and conducting won't.
</TEXT>
