<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     10-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Army Chief Says he Sympathizes with Chinese Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army chief said he sympathizes with
China and the troubles it faced when it crushed the pro-democracy
movement in June, the state newspaper reported Sunday.
   Burma faced a similar movement last year and crushed it in
September 1988 when troops killed thousands of protesters.
   The Working People's Daily said Brig. Gen. Khin Nyunt, who heads
the country's military intelligence, made the comments Friday at
the contruction site of a Chinese-built theater in Rangoon.
   ``I thank the Chinese government for sending engineers to
complete the construction in time while the country (China) is
suffering from the consequences of the disturbances,'' Khin Nyunt
said.
   Construction of the 1,500-seat theater, a gift from then-Chinese
President Li Xiannian in 1985 _ was suspended during Burma's
massive pro-democracy protests.
   Millions took to the streets in the student-led uprising against
years of authoritarian repression. It ended following a series of
crackdowns in which thousands were shot to death.
   Diplomats and dissidents say that several thousand pro-democracy
supporters have been arrested since July, when the two leading
opposition politicians, Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, were placed
under house arrest.
   The U.S. Embassy in Rangoon has said it has ``credible'' reports
that many of those arrested have been tortured, some to death. The
government denies the charge.
   China celebrated its 40th anniversary Sunday. On June 3-4,
troops marched on Beijing and hundreds, perhaps thousands, of
people were killed when the military crushed the student-led
protests for democracy.
</TEXT>
