<FIRST>r p AM-NJGovernor     10-01 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Governor,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Race For NJ Governor Turns Nasty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's race for governor has taken a
very nasty road with the two candidates taking turns denying their
opponent's latest allegation of wrongdoing or impropriety, and then
making one of their own.
   ``Once someone goes into the mud, he drags the other candidate
in with him,'' said Gov. Thomas H. Kean, the popular Republican who
is barred from the state constitution from running for a third
consecutive term. ``With campaigns like this, the voters lose.''
   The sharp volleys between seven-term Democratic Rep. James
Florio, 52, the front-runner in recent polls, and five-term
Republican Rep. James Courter, 47, have become more frequent. And a
televised debate last week granted both their most public forum yet.
   A Florio television commercial accuses Courter of dumping toxic
waste on his own property, but Courter says the allegation is
``just plain wrong.'' Florio, in turn, said a Courter accusation
that his law firm allows drug dealers back onto the street is
``slimy.''
   One of two gubernatorial races this year _ the other is in
Virginia _ the campaign has degenerated into an exchange of
personal attacks that have eclipsed top issues such tax reform,
drug abuse, high automobile insurance rates and abortion.
   In a raging battle over ethics, Courter accused Florio of
obtaining a free stake in land in Camden County. Florio said he
took out a loan to buy an interest in the land, which he eventually
donated to his alma mater, Trenton State College.
   Florio leveled his own conflict of interest charges, saying
Courter's law firm represented Westinghouse Electric Co., a defense
contractor, while Courter was a member of the Armed Services
Committee. Courter said his place on the committee was never
compromised.
   Three independent polls released last week show Florio with a
substantial lead over Courter. One, conducted by Political Media
Research Poll for a group of media outlets, showed Florio with a
14-point lead.
   Results of a poll released Saturday by the Eagleton Institute of
Rutgers University found Courter trailing by 23 points. A separate
poll by the Record of Hackensack found the Republican trailing by
16 points.
   The election is Nov. 7.
   The race comes only a year after a notoriously dirty U.S. Senate
campaign in New Jersey which featured, among other things,
unsuccessful Republican challenger Pete Dawkins calling Sen. Frank
Lautenberg a ``swamp dog.''
   ``I don't think there was ever much doubt that this
(gubernatorial race) was going to become a mudslinging and
name-calling campaign,'' said Rick Sinding, president of the Center
for Analysis of Public Issues in Princeton. ``Unfortunately, there
is a growing belief that negative campaigns work. In the debate,
they were like two little kids kicking sand on each other.''
   Leaders of each campaign insist their charges are accurate and
that the other side is distorting the truth. They both say they are
waging ``positive'' campaigns, but won't let their opponent's
charges go unchallenged.
   A Florio television advertisement saying the state was forced to
order Courter and his brother to remove drums of fuel oil from land
they owned clearly angered Courter. Environmental officials say the
spill of oil was not significant, but it took the Courters nearly
two years to remove the drums.
   ``I was the victim of a midnight dumper,'' said Courter.
   ``The clear implication in the ads is that Jim Courter utilized
his land as a toxic waste dump, and that's a vicious personal
attack,'' said Republican leader Robert Franks, an adviser to the
Courter campaign.
   Florio aides had similar comments about a Courter ad accusing
Florio of profiting from his law firm's defense of drug dealers.
   Florio, whose forte in Congress is environmental issues, wants
to counter pro-environment advertisements by Courter, who is rated
by the environmental lobby in Congress at the bottom of the state's
14-member delegation.
   Courter is attempting to paint Florio as soft on crime, saying
his opposition to a proposal that would loosen restrictions on
evidence favors criminals rather than victims.
</TEXT>
