<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-Reporter'sNotebook     10-01 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-Reporter's Notebook,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Notes From Africa's Last Colony</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For some U.N. soldiers in Namibia, life
is mostly fun and games. For others it's more like a bowl of cold
gruel.
   Troops from some nations, such as Finland, receive the full pay
provided by the United Nations and often frequent Windhoek's best
restaurants and liveliest discos. A number of Finns have bought
luxury sports cars that cost far less than in their homeland, where
imported vehicles face huge surcharges.
   The less fortunate Polish soldiers get the same pay as at home,
with their government pocketing the remainder of the U.N. stipend.
Off-duty Poles are most easily found at U.N. canteens or on public
buses.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Among the most popular U.N. troops are a group of Fijians who
arrived unannounced one night at the usually all-white Hotel
Stroblhof bar in the conservative desert town of Karibib.
   When they pulled out musical instruments and began an impromptu
concert, the Fijians initially drew withering stares. Eventually,
the regulars began to smile, and later they started dancing. The
Fijians are now the featured act on Wednesday and Saturday nights
at the Stroblhof.
   The Fijian contingent also includes some of the South Pacific
nation's top rugby players, who have joined the Karibib squad and
vastly improved the previously mediocre team.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   U.N. troops and Namibians have proved vigorous souvenir-hunters,
unwilling to settle for the run-of-the-mill gift shop trinkets.
   A group of 30 Malaysians were accused of hacking away chunks of
the Hoba meteorite, reportedly the largest on earth and an official
landmark in Namibia.
   The special license plates on U.N. vehicles (such as UNTAG 10,
UNTAG 11, etc.) have been disappearing so quickly that officials
decided to simply paint letters and numbers onto the bodies of the
vehicles rather than constantly try to replace the plates.
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said his 13-year-old son has a
friend who has acquired 17 plates.
   The head of the U.N. contingent, Martti Ahtisaari, still has his
original plates (UNTAG 1), but collectors are now offering more
than 400 rand ($150) for them, no questions asked.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, the black
independence movement, preserved its reputation for disorganization
when President Sam Nujoma returned from 30 years of exile Sept. 14.
   SWAPO leaders promised an afternoon press conference in
Katutura, the sprawling black neighborhood on the edge of Windhoek
but couldn't decide on a venue.
   About 100 journalists spent almost two hours randomly
criss-crossing the dusty, unmarked streets before they stumbled on
the location _ a private house with a driveway full of luxury cars
flying the SWAPO flag.
   However, dozens of other journalists, including a group of
Americans who had chartered a plane from South Africa to report on
Nujoma's homecoming, never found the SWAPO leader.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   White Namibians generally are suspicious of U.N. soldiers from
African nations, believing that the troops support SWAPO.
   Right-wing whites felt sure they had proof of Kenyan sympathies
following reports that the soldiers were wearing belts with stripes
of red, green and dark blue _ the colors of SWAPO.
   In fact, the belts are red, green and black _ the colors of
Kenya and official government issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
