<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-AtlantaMayor     10-01 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Mayor,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Mayor's Race Quietly Nears Election Day, As Former Mayor
Cruises</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a mayoral election in Atlanta this
Tuesday, but you'd be hard pressed to prove it, as the quiet return
of former Mayor Maynard Jackson has unfolded with hardly a hitch.
   Jackson, the city's mayor from 1974-82, has kept a low profile
during the two terms of his successor, Andrew Young. But at 51, he
remains popular _ so much so that his chief challenger, Fulton
County Commission Chairman Michael Lomax, suddenly quit the race in
August amid dismal poll showings.
   ``I'm just a nice guy,'' Jackson chuckles.
   At the last minute, veteran civil rights activist Hosea Williams
quit his City Council seat and entered the race, predicting a
miracle but also running, admittedly, to make Jackson put up some
kind of a fight.
   ``I've already accomplished one of my major victories _ to make
Maynard campaign,'' Williams said last week. ``If it hadn't been
for me, he would have walked back into City Hall scot-free.''
   But Williams has not gotten exactly the fight he sought. The
former mayor refused a one-on-one debate, even after Williams tried
to force the challenge by fasting, which only left him thinner and
weary. (The fast brought in one campaign contribution: a new pair
of suspenders from a backer.)
   With only $15,000 or so in campaign donations, Williams has been
forced to rely on a few radio ads to get his message out, along
with yard signs proclaiming him ``The Clique-Buster'' _ a slap at
Jackson, whom he brands part of a ``super-rich, small, black
elitist clique.''
   Jackson's staff has concentrated on making sure their supporters
bother to vote.
   ``The apathy out there is much stronger than I expected,''
Jackson said. ``We're fighting hard for a respectable turnout.
   ``What we're fighting for is a mandate. I want to make sure I'm
not walking up Calvary alone. The more people vote, the more people
feel invested in the future of the city.''
   Four longshots round out the non-partisan ballot: nightclub
comedian Jerry Farber, bus driver and anti-abortion activist
Mitchell Williams, Georgia Tech student Mark Teal, and Lafayette
Perry, who is unemployed.
   Young is ineligible for a third consecutive term, as was Jackson
eight years ago when he left the mayor's office for the life of a
high-paid bond lawyer. Young is now mounting a race for governor in
1990.
   The quiet of the campaign is surprising, considering the
presence of the talkative, growling Hosea Williams. News reports
barely mention the campaign, focusing instead on what Jackson's
third term will be like.
   Jackson, an erudite, eloquent man, became Atlanta's first black
mayor in 1973, five years after he turned some heads with a
longshot challenge to veteran Sen. Herman Talmadge.
   Now Jackson seems headed for coronation.
   ``Even I've been surprised,'' he said. ``That long out of
office, when you look at our numbers ...
   ``The toughest job in politics is being a mayor. Every day you
make 10 people happy and 10 people mad. People want _ people crave
_ strong leadership. And that's what I've always tried to give.''
   In his previous terms, Jackson was a bold young mayor locked in
contention with the city's largely white business community, as he
insisted on minority participation in city business. Other problems
arose: A 1977 garbage strike shook the city, and his public safety
commissioner quit in 1978 amid allegations that he had helped
supporters cheat on promotion exams.
   Though black himself, Williams has been a longtime critic of the
city's black power structure, saying those blacks in power have not
done enough for poor people. He blames Jackson for derailing the
city from its ``history of continuous progression.'' He charges
that under Jackson, crime increased, the police department was
demoralized and hit by corruption, and infrastructure needs went
unmet.
   But Jackson's eight years in office the opening of the city's
rapid transit system and the construction of a huge new airport
complex.
   This time out, he is courting white business support _ even
though he probably doesn't need it to win in a city where 61
percent of the 192,000 registered voters are black.
   Jackson's priorities this time are the problems of Atlanta and
numerous other cities: drug-fueled crime and a need for low-income
housing.
   Jackson calls his platform ``five for the future'' _ fighting
drugs and crime, building better housing, promoting economic
development, well-managed government and improving the quality of
life.
   That is not the agenda of a bond attorney.
   ``I love the law,'' he said. ``I love the practice of law. But
the reality is that politics is my ministry. I want to do something
to make a difference. The only thing I have in mind is serving this
city as mayor.
   ``We're going to show ourselves, and the nation, how great a
city can be.''
</TEXT>
