<SECOND>AM-BRF--Political Brawl,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians Exchange Punches at Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fistfights and scuffling broke out
among supporters of rival candidates when 6,000 people gathered
Sunday for the filing of nominations for the leadership of a major
political party.
   About 50 riot police moved in to disperse the rival groups. No
one was injured, no arrests were made and order was restored within
15 minutes, police Superintendent Fauzi Shaari told reporters.
   Nominations for party president were being filed at the
headquarters of the Malaysian Indian Congress, the third major
partner in the governing National Front coalition of 12 Malay,
Chinese, Indian and other parties.
   Sangilimuthu Samy Vellu, seeking re-election as party president,
arrived first with supporters bearing banners and placards.
   Party Deputy President Sinniah Subramaniam, another candidate
for president, appeared 90 minutes later, and scuffling and
fistfights broke out when Vellu's supporters jeered at
Subramaniam's supporters.
   Nominations proceeded after order was restored, and 15 were
received for party elections on Oct. 15. Vellu was considered the
front-runner.
