<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-Poland     10-01 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Poland,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>More East Germans Flock to Warsaw Embassy After Train for West Leaves</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of East Germans, including some who
missed a special train to West Germany hours earlier, arrived
Sunday at the West German Embassy in Warsaw hoping to follow their
compatriots to the West.
   Up to 100 new refugees sat glumly in cars or milled about the
street in front of the embassy.
   Several said they were certain there eventually would be another
``freedom train'' for them.
   Juerg Sachs of Schwerin, in northern East Germany, said he and
his wife, Daniela, arrived in Warsaw at 2 a.m. Sunday just before
the special train left. He said they were not able to reach the
embassy in time to catch the train that departed at 2:50 a.m.
   Sachs, 29, said he had been reassured by an official inside the
embassy compound who told him, ``You missed the train, but don't
worry, because there will be another solution in four to six
weeks.''
   ``Better six weeks in Warsaw than another six years in the
GDR,'' Sachs said, using the initials for the formal name of his
Communist homeland, the German Democratic Republic.
   About 800 East German refugees in Warsaw and 6,000 in Prague,
Czechoslovakia, were allowed to travel to West Germany in special
trains late Saturday and Sunday under terms of a historic East-West
accord.
   However, East Germany said it now expects West Germany to resume
``normal international customs'' at its embassies, indicating it
wants the Bonn government to bar refugees from its diplomatic
compounds.
   Poland's official PAP news agency said Sunday that East Germany
showed ``high flexibility and understanding for this human
dimension of the problems'' in allowing the exodus.
   Poland has a new government led by non-Communists, but it has
handled the refugee issue cuatiously, trying not to antagonize East
Germany, a Warsaw Pact ally.
   PAP's report Sunday said again that Poland had considered the
refugees a problem to be settled between the two Germanys. It said
it had only provided logistical and technical assistance to the
talks that led to the East-West accord.
   The agency said the issue should not ``lead to deteriorating ...
relations with either of the German states.''
   Poland took a more liberal approach toward the refugees than its
hard-line Communist neighbor, Czechoslovakia. Polish officials let
the refugees move freely around the city but in Prague they were
crowded into the embassy compound.
   A West German Embassy worker said Sunday that East Germany's
decision to let the refugees travel to the West would not
discourage more from coming to Poland.
   ``I think just the opposite,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
