<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Arafat     10-01 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Arafat,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Arrives for Japanese Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat arrived Sunday for his
first visit to Japan as a guest of the government, which is
expected to hear his views on prospects for peace in the Middle
East.
   During his four-day visit, Arafat is to meet with Prime Minister
Toshiki Kaifu, former Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, Foreign Minister
Taro Nakayama and leaders of the governing and opposition parties.
   Officials said the government will listen to Arafat's views on
the Middle East peace process, including recent proposals by
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt on election procedures and
possibilities for direct dialogue between Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Foreign Ministry officials said the government invitation was
intended to to show Japan's appreciation for Arafat's U.N. speech
in Geneva in December, when he renounced violence and laid out
ideas for peace.
   One official said the invitation was aimed at bolstering
Arafat's moderate policy amid reported pressures from PLO
hard-liners advocating a return to terrorist tactics.
   ``We have the view that Chairman Arafat has very limited time''
to bolster his position, the official said on condition of
anonymity.
   The government also invited Arafat as part of its own efforts to
help seek peace in the Middle East through contacts with both the
Arabs and Israelis, the official said.
   The government's invitation to Arafat was the first to a PLO
leader since the organization was founded in 1964.
   Officials have said the government was welcoming Arafat as
chairman of the PLO, not as president of the self-proclaimed state
of Palestine.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service, in a dispatch from Tunisia on
Saturday, quoted Arafat as saying he will urge Japan to recognize
the state of Palestine.
   Arafat previously visited Japan in October 1981 at the
invitation of the Arab-Japanese Parliamentarian League.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency reported Saturday that
Arafat will make an official visit to China on Wednesday and
Thursday.
</TEXT>
