<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0688 10-01 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0688,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Arabs Killed By Troops, Alleged Collaborator Stabbed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with one more Palestinian killed, three
wounded; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and killed four Palestinians in
clashes in the occupied lands Sunday and Arab activists stabbed to
death a man they accused of collaborating with Israel, the army and
Arab hospitals said.
   In the Gaza Strip, Moslem fundamentalists issued a new leaflet
calling on Palestinians to escalate their 21-month-old uprising and
to ``continue to kill collaborators.''
   The 700,000 Arab residents of the seaside strip were banned from
entering Israel for a third consecutive day as Israelis celebrated
Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year.
   The holiday ended at sundown Sunday, but the closure remains in
effect until Monday morning.
   Security was tight throughout Israel as Israelis attended prayer
services at synagogues or flocked to resort sites. In the occupied
Gaza Strip and West Bank, soldiers battled stone-throwing
Palestinian protesters, reportedly wounding 25 of the demonstrators.
   The most violent clash was reported at Gaza's Nuseirat refugee
camp, where troops shot and killed 17-year-old Nidal Saidam and
wounded at least 14 other Palestinians, including Saidam's sister
Ikram, 16, Arab doctors said. They said Saidam died of a gunshot
wound to the head.
   The army command confirmed the death and four wounded and said
it was checking further.
   At least four Palestinians were reported wounded in other
clashes in the Gaza Strip.
   In the Gaza village of Bani Suhaila, uprising activists armed
with daggers and clubs stabbed to death Saleh Al-Kera, 25, whom
they accused of collaborating with Israeli authorities, Arab
reporters said.
   The army confirmed the death, which raised to 123 the number of
alleged collaborators slain by Palestinians in the revolt.
   Israeli soldiers or civilians have killed 581 Palestinians
during the revolt, and 40 Israelis have been killed.
   ``Continue to kill collaborators,'' urged a leaflet distributed
Sunday in Gaza by Moslem extremists from the Islamic Jihad group.
   Some Palestinian notables have condemned the hasty slayings of
suspected collaborators.
   The leaflet also ordered two general strike days this month and
told Palestinian activists to keep confiscating Israeli-issued
magnetic identity cards required for Gazans to travel to Israel.
   Arab activists have confiscated about 10,000 of the 60,000 cards
issued by Israel as a security precaution. Last week, activists
began returning the cards in what was seen as a victory for
Israel's tighter security measures.
   Sunday's clashes spread to the West Bank, where three
Palestinians were shot and killed, according to Arab and military
accounts.
   Army officials said a military patrol was attacked by youths
hurling concrete blocks from rooftops at the marketplace in Nablus,
the West Bank's largest Palestinian city.
   They said soldiers opened fire when their lives were in danger,
wounding 17-year-old Immad Kharaz, who fell from the roof and died.
Arab reporters said his body was removed from a hospital and buried
in a funeral procession attended by more than 400 Palestinians.
   In the West Bank village of Arabe, troops fired plastic bullets
after being attacked with stones and bottles, killing a protester,
military officials said. Arab reporters identified the victim as
Khalil Abu Ziad, 16, and said he died instantly when several
bullets pierced his chest.
   At the Aida refugee camp near Bethlehem, soldiers arresting
three suspects were attacked by a mob, an army official said. He
said the soldiers shot to death one Palestinian and wounded three.
   In clashes in Nablus, Arabe and the West Bank's Balata refugee
camp, four other Palestinians were shot and wounded, Arab hospital
officials said. The army said it was checking the reports.
</TEXT>
