<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0666 10-01 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Predicts Doom for Catastrophic Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS top 13 grafs to move up Foley comments on catastrophic
health vote; picks up 14th graf pvs, ``On the''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley on Sunday
predicted the House this week probably will vote to repeal Medicare
catastrophic health care coverage that it enacted last year for
some 33 million elderly Americans.
   Many beneficiaries, especially the wealthier among them, have
balked at having to pay premiums this year of up to $800 to cover
the hospital and physicians' bills for lower-income retirees.
   ``I hope personally that the program is retained on a modified
form,'' Foley, D-Wash., said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' program.
``But ... there are a great number of Republicans and some
Democrats in the House who are in favor of repeal. If I were
guessing today, I think it probably would be repealed.''
   Foley also said he doubts that the reconciliation bill will be
completed by an Oct. 16 deadline. Broad across-the-board spending
cuts in both domestic and military programs will take effect
automatically then unless it is.
   ``We might have some few days in which there would be a
technical sequestration, that is an across-the-board cutting
through executive order of all the accounts,'' Foley said.
   However, he added, ``I don't think that's going to be a
permanent situation.''
   In other House action, a long-awaited bill to protect the
nation's waterways from oil spills is expected to get to the floor
this week after months of committee hearings and backroom
negotiations.
   Similar legislation already has passed the Senate. But the
version that emerged from a House committee was opposed by so many
members that the drafters renegotiated a new proposal that could be
sensibly managed on the floor.
   The Exxon-Valdez tanker accident last spring that dumped 10
million gallons of crude oil into Prince William Sound inspired the
congressional review of liability laws and legislation to
strengthen them.
   Though specifics weren't available last week, congressional
staffers and others with an interest in the House bill believe the
main sticking point _ pre-emption of state's rights to enact laws
stricter than federal statutes _ will have to be worked out by the
full House through floor votes.
   Other items such as limits on how much the federal government
can charge oil companies for spills are expected to be included in
the revised legislation before it goes to the floor Thursday.
   The House also will continue work this week on reducing the
federal deficit through the bill known as the Budget Reconciliation
Act of 1989.
   This week, members will decide whether to repeal catastrophic
medical insurance for retirees or to reduce benefits, and choose
between competing plans for increasing child-care assistance to
low-income families.
   On the Senate side, the Finance Committee begins work on a
package of spending reductions and revenue increases designed to
cut the budget deficit by about $17 billion this fiscal year.
   The biggest issue facing the panel is whether to reduce the tax
on capital gains, which President Bush recommended as a saving
incentive and temporary revenue-raising measure and the House
approved last week.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said Sunday on the same
NBC program that he has the votes to defeat the House-passed
version of President Bush's capital gains measure.
   ``It is so bad, so wrong for the economy,'' he said. ``It will
do for the deficit what crack does for the user: a quick short high
followed by a long, painful depression.''
   Mitchell, however, said Bush's ``irresponsible position ...
makes it extremely difficult to prevent any tax cut from
occurring'' on a very close vote.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the finance panel, is
recommending a partial restoration of tax deductibility of
contributions to Individual Retirement Accounts, or IRAs, as an
alternative to the capital gains cuts.
   Meanwhile, conference committees will be continue on several
appropriations bills telling each department how much and where it
can spend money.
   Last week, there was a negotiating session between House and
Senate conferees thrashing out the defense authorization bill _ one
of the stickiest in the package.
   A major sticking point is how much the government will spend on
Star Wars in fiscal 1990: The Senate has appropriated $3.7 billion
but the House wants to spend only $3.1 billion.
   The House Government Operations subcommittee on employment and
housing continues its investigation into scandals at the Department
of Housing and Urban Development with a return appearance by
self-described influence peddler Paul Manafort.
   Stonewalled by the leading players in the scandal, the
subcommittee wants to job Manafort's memory about projects linked
to him by other witnesses since his first appearance in June.
   Back then, Manafort acknowledged that he used his influence
among political appointees at HUD to steer millions of dollars in
government renovation funds to a housing project in which he shared
ownership.
   However, he his Alexandria, Va., firm of Black, Manafort, Stone
&amp; Kelly did relatively little HUD business. Since then, other
witnesses have connected the firm with projects in New Jersey,
Connecticut, Georgia and Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
