<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0696 10-01 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain In Southeast Threatens Flooding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after lead to UPDATE with tornado hitting Georgia,
killing two.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 7 inches of rain fell Sunday over parts of the Southeast,
causing lowland flooding and prompting widespread flash flood
watches, and snow fell in parts of Montana.
   In the southern Georgia town of Moultrie, a tornado killed a
woman and an infant, injured a dozen more people and destroyed a
church in a 10-mile rampage Sunday afternoon.
   Rising water forced evacuation of more than 50 people from one
North Carolina mobile home park.
   Flash flood watches were posted into early Monday morning over
southeastern West Virginia, western Virginia, western North
Carolina, western South Carolina and northern Georgia.
   Two inches of rain or more fell Saturday and Sunday over western
sections of the Carolinas and northern Georgia, as well as across
the western Florida Panhandle.
   Athens, Ga., got 7.64 inches of rain during the 24 hours up to
noon EDT.
   Record flooding was predicted on the Oconee River at Penfield,
Ga. Flood stage is 11 feet and the river reached 19.7 feet Sunday,
with a crest of about 24 feet forecast Monday, the National Weather
Service said.
   Authorities in Gaston County, N.C., evacuated 53 residents of 30
mobile homes in a low-lying park, said Tom Riley, Gaston County
communications coordinator. Lincoln County authorities helped
evacuate residents of a house threatened by a nearby overflowing
creek, said Bill Hoover, a dispatcher with the Lincoln County
Sheriff's Department.
   ``We have just urged caution. It's probably as bad as it's going
to get,'' said a dispatcher in Polk County, N.C., where three low
bridges were covered by water.
   Rain began falling in western North Carolina late Thursday ``and
it's been raining since,'' said Hank Moore of the weather service
in Asheville. He said 2 to 7 inches had fallen in some areas.
   ``We're saturated not only from (hurricane) Hugo, but from
rainfall earlier in the month,'' Moore said.
   A few back roads in south-central Tennessee were closed by
water, the weather service said.
   Creeks in Pulaski County, Va., were nearly full and there was
minor flooding along Back Creek, the weather service said, but rain
stopped during the morning and no serious flooding was expected
there.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
2.41 inches at Ozark, Ala.; 2.0 at Athens, Ga.; 1.88 at Greer,
S.C.; 1.46 at Macon, Ga.; 1.43 at Huntsville, Ala.; 1.42 at
Hickory, N.C.; 1.38 at Dothan, Ala.; 1.30 at Atlanta; 1.24 at
Marietta, Ga.; 1.23 at Panama City, Fla.; 1.15 at Anniston, Ala.;
and 1.02 at Charlotte, N.C.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended northward into southern
Pennsylvania, central Ohio, Kentucky and southern Illinois.
   Elsewhere, showers reached from South Dakota across northern
Wyoming into south-central Montana, with snow at higher elevations
of Montana near Lewiston.
   A cold front in the Rockies kicked up wind gusting to 71 mph at
Boulder, Colo.
   Livestock advisories were posted over northern Wyoming because
of a combination of cold, gusty wind and rain changing to snow,
with accumulations of up to 5 inches predicted in the Big Horn
Mountains of north-central Wyoming.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 95 at Phoenix. Sunday's low for the
Lower 48 states was 24 at Gunnison, Colo., and Union Village, Vt.
</TEXT>
