<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-01 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka's Governing Party Offers New Elections in Peace Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's governing party on
Sunday offered to dissolve Parliament and hold new elections if
that would help restore peace to this nation crippled by ethnic
violence.
   The United National Party issued a statement saying a party
committee had made the recommendations in a report to President
Ranasinghe Premadasa. There was no immediate response from the
president.
   Sri Lanka, an island off the southern coast of India, is torn by
a separatist war with minority Tamils and a violent backlash by
majority Sinhalese. More than 11,000 people have been killed since
the Tamil insurgency started in 1983, and 5,000 others have been
killed in the Sinhalese violence.
   In another political development Sunday, the most powerful of
the Tamil rebel groups, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, said
it was willing to participate in elections in northeastern Sri
Lanka if the present provincial council was dissolved and Indian
peacekeeping troops return home.
   The government has been trying to have the 42,000 Indian
soldiers withdrawn and to increase Tamil autonomy in the northeast.
India sent troops into Sri Lanka under an India-brokered peace
accord between the Sinhalese and Tamils that collapsed. India has
promised to withdraw all of its troops by the end of the year.
   The governing party's statement also said its committee had
recommended the lifting of emergency regulations, suspension of the
anti-terrorist act, granting of amnesty to all political prisoners,
and offering protection to Sinhalese militants willing to put down
their weapons.
   The Sinhalese-dominated government declared a unilateral
cease-fire Wednesday in the struggle with militant Sinhalese.
However, government sources said it would not be extended beyond
Tuesday unless the radicals make a positive response.
   The government has asked them to renounce their violence. The
militatns say they are fighting because the government offered too
many concessions to the Tamils.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus living in northeastern Sri
Lanka, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's population of 16 million.
They claim the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who account for 75
percent of the population, discriminate against them.
   A senior military official said Sunday that at least 28 people,
including three Buddhist monks, had been killed in the Sinhalese
violence during the cease-fire.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 789
Sinhalese militants had surrendered during the same period.
</TEXT>
