<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Rightists     10-01 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Rightists,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ultrarightists Win Council Seats in Several Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ultrarightist Republican
Party, led by a former Nazi SS trooper, won its first city council
seats Sunday in Cologne and several other West German cities,
according to television reports.
   Throngs of demonstrators, some of them carrying signs reading
``Nazis Out!'' held protest rallies against the Republicans in a
number of cities during municipal elections across North
Rhine-Westphalia state.
   The Republicans won their first council seats in Cologne,
Leverkusen, Dortmund, Duesseldorf, Gelsenkirchen, Hamm and Hagen,
according to projections by the ARD television network Sunday night.
   It said the party was expected to get between 6.2 percent and
7.4 percent of the vote in those cities. Five percent is required
for a party to win representation on a council.
   ARD said the Republicans were failing to get 5 percent of the
vote in many other cities and towns.
   The balloting was for governing councils in cities, districts,
towns and villages across densely populated North Rhine-Westphalia.
   ARD said Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union was
suffering serious losses and the Social Democrats, the opposition
party in the federal government, were picking up some votes.
   According to ARD's projections, the Christian Democrats would
receive 37.7 percent of the vote throughout the sate, down 4.5
percent from municipal elections five years ago. The Social
Democrats, who hold power in many of the largest cities, were
expected to win 43 percent of the vote, up by .5 percent.
   The Republicans entered the North Rhine-Westphalia municipal
elections following successes earlier this year.
   In balloting for the European Parliament elections last June the
party received 7.1 percent of the West German vote and gained six
seats in the Parliament.
   The Republicans won seats in the West Berlin state legislature
in January and also made gains in June municipal elections in the
states of Saarland and Rhineland-Palatinate.
   The Republicans advocate ultraconservative and nationalist
policies but deny accusations that they are neo-Nazis. They argue
that new generations of Germans should be absolved of the guilt for
Nazi crimes.
   Franz Schoenhuber, the Republicans' national leader, was a
Waffen SS soldier in World War II.
</TEXT>
