<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Meeting,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report ANC of South Africa Meets Group Linked to Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African group with close ties to that
country's governing National Party met in England Sunday with
members of the African National Congress, a news agency reported.
   The Afrikaner Broederbond and ANC members met near London for
talks expected to last about two days, according to Press
Association, Britain's domestic news agency.
   No details were given on the topics of their discussions.
   A Foreign Office spokesman in London said: ``We are aware of the
meeting. But it is not being organized by the British government.
We have no information about the nature of the talks.''
   Afrikaner Broederbond is headed by Wimpie de Klerk, a brother of
South Africa's news President F.W. de Klerk. The organization
consists of prominent figures believed to be close to senior
government ministers, Press Association said.
   The agency said Thabo Mbeki, ANC information officer, was
leading the delegation of the outlawed black nationalist
organization.
   The ANC has dismissed President de Klerk's pledges of
black-white power-sharing and vowed to continue its fight against
South Africa's white minority government.
   The ANC formed an exile headquarters in Zambia and began a
campaign of sabotage against South Africa and its racial separation
policies in 1961. It was banned in South Africa the previous year.
