<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--PilotKilled     10-01 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pilot Killed,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Pilot Killed In Small-Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAVER FALLS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane being flown by a
USAir pilot ``folded'' up in midair and plunged into a field,
killing the pilot, authorities said.
   James R. Grunzke, 41, of Beaver Falls, was pronounced dead at
the scene, about one mile from the Beaver County Airport, by Beaver
County Coroner Wayne Tatalovich. Police said Grunzke was carrying
documents that identified him as a USAir captain.
   Grunzke had been with the airline for 11 years and usually flew
DC-9s, said USAir spokeswoman Susan Young.
   The private plane, described as a 42-year-old two-seater with a
wingspan estimated at 30 feet, was making its final approach to
land when the accident happened about 11:45 a.m. Saturday, said
airport manager Dan Donatella.
   ``It apparently was structural failure,'' said Jack Mintier,
assistant police chief. ``Eyewitnesses said one of the wings just
folded back and the plane went straight down.''
   There were no passengers.
   The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating the crash.
