<FIRST>r a AM-Justice-Suicide     10-01 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Suicide,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Supreme Court Justice Dies Of Self-Inflicted Gunshot Wound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chief justice of the Kansas
Supreme Court committed suicide by shooting himself in the head,
authorities said.
   Harold R. Fatzer, 79, was found Saturday at his Topeka home.
W.W. Scamman, Shawnee County district coroner, ruled the death a
suicide after an autopsy.
   Scamman said Fatzer apparently did not leave a note, but that he
had been depressed for medical reasons.
   ``He had been ill,'' Scamman said. ``He had several things I
think, some heart disease and probably a malignancy in his lung.''
   Fatzer, who served on the Kansas Supreme Court from 1956 to 1977
and was chief justice from 1971 to 1977, also served as the state
attorney general from 1949 to 1954, when he became well-known for
gambling raids he led.
   He had been appointed to preside this week over a Kansas Court
of Appeals panel thatwill hear a case in the courtroom named for
him in the Kansas Judicial Center.
   The Fatzer room was dedicated June 23 in recognition of Fatzer's
efforts in the early 1970s to persuade the Legislature to build the
center, which houses the state Law Library, Supreme Court, Court of
Appeals and attorney general's offices.
   Fatzer is survived by his wife, Frances, a sister, a son and
three grandsons.
</TEXT>
