<FIRST>r a AM-Governors'Conference     10-01 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors' Conference,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midwest Governors Open Conference to Discuss Agriculture, Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYA L. WESLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Midwest is shaking its ``rust belt'' image
and should be promoted as a region with hard workers, a healthy
economy and less crime, participants in the Midwestern Governors'
Conference said Sunday.
   ``What we're trying to do is promote this region,'' Wisconsin
Gov. Tommy G. Thompson said as governors and other representatives
of 13 states gathered for the start of the 27th annual conference,
which continues through Tuesday.
   Thompson, the conference host, said news media have dismissed
the Midwest as part of the ``rust belt,'' referring to the loss of
traditional manufacturing jobs when industries leave a region. But
he said the Midwest has begun to shake that image.
   Gov. Terry E. Branstad of Iowa agreed, citing a recent article
in Newsweek magazine.
   ``The heartland is hot,'' he said. ``I think this region is in a
very enviable position.''
   Branstad said the area must market its strong work ethic,
healthy economy, educational programs, low cost of living and
relatively low crime rate.
   Speakers scheduled to appear at the conference include U.S.
Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and Deputy Secretary of State
Lawrence Eagleburger.
   During business sessions of the conference, Thompson said the
governors would work to develop cooperative efforts to fight
illegal drugs and to protect the environment.
   Also, governors of the five states of the northern Mississippi
River will sign a Mississippi Pact to protect the river, which
Thompson called an environmental and economic resource.
   The states in the Midwestern Governors' Association are
Wisconsin, Missouri, Minnesota, Iowa, Illinois, North Dakota, South
Dakota, Kansas, Michigan, Ohio, Indiana, Kentucky and Nebraska.
</TEXT>
