<FIRST>r a AM-GangViolence     10-01 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gang Violence,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Anti-Gang Sweeps Net Thousand Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police task force trying to suppress gang
violence arrested more than 1,000 people during weekend sweeps of
gang territories in Los Angeles and San Fernando Valley,
authorities said Sunday.
   Hundreds of officers were deployed in both areas Friday night
and again Saturday night, watching for any offenses and checking
for warrants.
   Police made 472 arrests Friday night and 624 arrest Saturday
night. Of the total, 345 were suspected gang members, police said.
   Gang attacks continued despite the sweeps, the latest in a
long-running series of sweeps that Police Chief Daryl Gates calls
Operation Hammer.
   A 15-year-old boy, Nelson R. Alas, an alleged gang member, was
shot and killed early Sunday in Hollywood, said Detective Bill
Humphry. Alas and another youth were on a bicycle when they were
confronted by a gang.
   Words were exchanged before the unidentified gang members shot
Alas to death, Humphry said. The other youth was not hurt.
   A spate of drive-by shootings, a typical method of gang attack,
killed one man and wounded seven people in greater Los Angeles
between Friday evening and early Saturday morning.
