<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-Beatification     10-01 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Beatification,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Beatifies Spanish Martyrs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Sunday beatified 26
Spaniards who were killed during anti-church violence at the
outbreak of the Spanish civil war in 1936.
   The Spaniards and three other church figures were beatified at
an outdoor Mass in St. Peter Square attended by about 30,000
people. Anglican leader Robert Runcie, the archbishop of
Canterbury, also took part.
   Speaking of the Spaniards, the pontiff said none was ``entangled
in political questions.''
   ``But nevertheless in the climate of the historical moment in
which they lived, they were dragged out into the storm of religious
persecution,'' he said, speaking in Spanish.
   The Spaniards were killed in mid-1936 at the beginning of the
war when the church in Spain suffered a wave of violence and hate.
   The others beatified Sunday were three 19th-century figures:
Geltrude Caterina Comensoli, an Italian woman who founded a
religious order; Francesca Anna Cirer, a Spanish woman who founded
a convent, and the Rev. Lorenzo Salvi, an Italian priest.
   In the Roman Catholic Church, beatification is one step away
from possible sainthood.
   Twelve of the Spanish martyrs were killed at Manzanares,
including the Rev. Vincente Diez Tejerina, the Rev. Anatolio Garcia
Nozal, and the Rev. Justiniano Cuesta Redondo.
   Among the nine killed at Carabanchel Bajo were the Rev. Manuel
Perez Jimenez and the Rev. Felipe Valcabado Granado.
   Three were slain in Urda, including the Rev. Pedro Largob
Redondo, and two were killed in Carrion de Calatrava.
   Many of the victims were students.
</TEXT>
