<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Clouthier 2ndLd-Writethru a0711 10-01 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Clouthier, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0711,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate Killed in Auto Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs with MINOR EDITING; INSERTS 4 grafs after
11th pvs `The government...' to UPDATE with more reax to death; pickup
graf 12 pvs `After his...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manuel J. Clouthier, the conservative
National Action Party's candidate in the 1988 presidential
election, and a political colleague were killed Sunday in an
auto-truck accident, police reported.
   In last year's balloting, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the
candidate of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, won
the presidency with slightly more than 50 percent of the vote.
Clouthier placed third with 17 percent.
   Clouthier, a wealthy businessman, was 55. He was on the campaign
trail again for his party in northern Mexico when he perished.
   A police report said Clouthier and Javier Calvo Manriquez,
National Action's Sinaloa state party chairman, were killed in a
head-on collision with a truck on the highway between Culiacan and
Mazatlan in Sinaloa, Clouthier's home state.
   It said Calvo Manriquez was driving the 1986 Dodge Dart.
   ``It happened around 11:30 a.m. .... They both died almost
instantly,'' Joel Cortes Escutia, a highway police duty officer at
the state capital of Culiacan, said in a telephone interview.
   Silvino Silva, editor of the newspaper Noroeste in Culiacan,
said the two men ``were on their way to Mazatlan to meet with
Ernesto Ruffo (governor-elect of Baja California).'' They had
scheduled a campaign rally for Sunday afternoon.
   Although Clouthier's third-place finish in 1988 had been
disappointing for National Action, his party made history with
Ruffo's July 2 win in Baja California.
   Ruffo will become the first opposition state governor in Mexico
in six decades when he is installed in office on Nov. 1.
   Clouthier and Ruffo were campaigning in Sinaloa for their
party's candidates in races for 18 city mayors Oct. 15.
   The government news agency Notimex quoted human rights activist
Rosario Ibarra de Piedra as saying Clouthier's death ``represents a
great loss for the political fight in Mexico.''
   Interior Secretary Fernando Gutierrez Barrios, the government's
chief political officer, sent condolences to Clouthier's family and
to National Action.
   Leftist leader Heberto Castillo called Clouthier's death ``a
hard blow for democratic pluralism.''
   ``He was a strong, courageous man of very defined political
ideology,'' Castillo told reporters.
   Carles Abedrop Avila, a former president of the Mexican Bankers'
Association, called Clouthier ``a great businessman and leader, an
honest and sincere fighter.''
   After his defeat in 1988, Clouthier continued to campaign
against election fraud, which he said has kept the Institutional
Revolutionary Party in power since 1929. At one point, Clouthier
staged a hunger strike at a major highway intersection in downtown
Mexico City.
   In the 1988 balloting, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a breakaway member
of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, came in second at the
head of a leftist coalition with 31 percent of the vote.
   After the returns were announced, Clouthier toured the country,
demanding the results be annulled and saying the election had been
``filthy.''
   ``Anyone who has a speck of decency, and I refer to Carlos
Salinas de Gortari in case he has any, can't shout victory in the
dirt that passed for elections,'' Clouthier said.
   Friends said Clouthier became active politically after President
Jose Lopez Portillo's government expropriated private Mexican banks
in 1982.
   One friend quoted him as saying, ``Lopez Portillo turned me into
a politician when he did that. I saw the power and the rigidity of
the presidential system and I decided to struggle to change that.''
   Clouthier ran for Sinaloa governor in 1986 but lost to the
Institutional Revolutionary Party candidate.
   In the 1988 presidential campaign, Clouthier advocated free
enterprise and an end to state controls over the economy and
denounced corruption and vote fraud.
   In the following years, he worked to unify his fractious
National Action Party into a political force and rally Mexico's
splintered conservatives.
   An agricultural engineer who at one time taught biology at the
University of Sinaloa, Clouthier sold most of his investments in
industrial companies and dedicated himself to truck farming and
politics.
   Clouthier was born June 13, 1934, in Culiacan.
   He was a fan of American football, which he played in high
school and for six years in a football league. He graduated from
the Technological Institute of Monterrey and was a leader of the
Mexican Employers' Federation council for more than 10 years.
   He is survived by his widow, Leticia Carrillo de Clouthier, and
10 children. The youngest are twins, a boy and a girl 15 years old.
</TEXT>
