<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Homeland     10-01 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Homeland,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeland Leader Offers Referendum on Rejoining South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUMBANE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a nominally
independent black homeland told a crowd of 15,000 people at a
funeral service Sunday that if they want a referendum on rejoining
South Africa he will arrange it.
   Maj. Gen. Bantu Holomisa, who took power in the Xhosa homeland
of Transkei in a bloodless coup in December 1988, addressed the
crowd during the funeral for a Thembu clan chief, King Sabata
Dalindyebo, who opposed the territory being declared independent in
1976.
   Dalindyebo, a relative of African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela, died in Lusaka, Zambia, in 1986 and his body was
sent home for burial. But the homeland leaders, fearing
demonstrations of support, buried the body in a commoner's
graveyard.
   The body was exhumed last week for reburial in the chief's
cemetery.
   Transkei is one of four black homelands South African's
white-dominated government has declared independent, but they are
not recognized by any other country. Most black South Africans
oppose the homeland system because it deprives the residents of
South African citizenship, residence, work and pension rights.
   There were anti-Holomisa chants among the crowd before the
33-year-old military officer took the stage with major South
African anti-apartheid figures such as Mandela's wife, Winnie.
   But by the end of Holomisa's speech, delivered in the Xhosa
language, many people were shouting ``Amandla!'' which means
``power.''
   Holomisa said if the people of Transkei wanted a referendum on
rejoining South Africa, he would organize it. He did not specify in
his short speech how the people would make their desire known and
there is no indication the South African government would accept
such a decision.
   Holomisa said he had allowed the exhumation and reburial of
Dalindyebo's remains ``because the people wanted it.''
   Dalindyebo was the traditional leader of Thembuland, which
covers most of Transkei. He was forced out of office by his cousin,
Kaiser Matanzima, in 1975 and fled to Lusaka, where he joined the
ANC.
   The South African government supported Matanzima because he had
agreed to Transkei becoming the first independent homeland as part
of the apartheid policy of creating separate nations for each black
tribe.
</TEXT>
