<HEAD>Church Quarrel Erupts into Fatal Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore editor's note. SUBS last graf with
6 grafs to UPDATE with details of shooting.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quarrel during a deacons' meeting at a church
erupted in gunfire that left two men dead and another wounded
Sunday, police said.
   The shooting occurred shortly before 1:30 p.m. during a meeting
among the four deacons and a secretary at the Living Testimony
Baptist Church in Dallas, said Sgt. Jim Chandler. The secretary was
not injured.
   ``All we know right now is that it appears that there was a
dispute among deacons. We're not sure what the argument was
about,'' said Detective H.E. Johnson.
   Two counts of capital murder and one count of attempted murder
were filed against one of the deacons, Gerald King, 30, who
remained at large Sunday, Chandler said.
   Jack Earl Ray, 51, died at Methodist Medical Center and Artis
Weaver, 60, died at Parkland Memorial Hospital, both from gunshot
wounds to the chest, authorities said.
   Billy Weaver, 39, was in fair condition at a local hospital with
a gunshot wound to the lower back, officials said.
   The shooting occurred in the church finance room _ where
donations are usually counted _ shortly after services ended,
according to police and witnesses. Several church members were
inside or just outside the church.
   About five minutes after the meeting commenced, witnesses said
they heard shouting from the church, followed by a series of
gunshots.
   ``They just started running and screaming, `He shot them,'''
Alvetta Taylor, a Sunday school teacher and longtime church member,
told The Dallas Morning News.
   King fled from the church in a car with his wife, Ms. Taylor
said.
   ``When he came out, his wife asked him what was wrong,'' she
said. ``She threw him into the car and drove off.''
   King was believed armed with a medium-caliber revolver, Chandler
said, and police also were searching for his wife.
