<FIRST>r e BC-BurnsandHope     10-01 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Burns and Hope,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burns and Hope Still Have Their Funny Bones</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Burns and Bob Hope added their ages and
called the first show they ever worked together ``179 Years of
Comedy.''
   At Madison Square Garden on Sunday night, Burns, 93, and Hope,
86, proved their funny bones still work _ though both kidded that
not everything does. Also, their timing and memory are still on.
And both sing better than Miss U.S.A., Gretchen Polhemus.
   Miss Universe, Angela Visser of Holland, fared better, just
exchanging quips, aided by cue cards, with Hope _ who has made
pretty girl walk-ons a tradition.
   In the show of nearly three hours, both comedians told age and
sex jokes, the latter mainly of the kind you could repeat to your
family later. Both told some jokes surely as old as they are. The
audience laughed as loud at those as at ones they hadn't heard
before.
   Hope's jokes flow fast and are many, about golf, flying,
doctors, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan and his son's running for
Congress. ``I didn't know what to do with my life savings anyway.
It kept him from writing a book about me.''
   Burns spent all his time on stage puffing on a cigar and most of
it sitting in a swivel chair equipped with ashtray. He told about
starting in vaudeville, changing his name, his acts and his
partners.
   Then, charmingly reminiscent, he said, ``When I was 27, I had
good talent. And I was married to her 38 years.'' As a finale, with
Hope taking the late Gracie Allen's part, talking about her zany
relatives, the two did a Burns and Allen routine, dancing time
steps between punchlines.
   He isn't going to retire, Burns said spunkily. He's still making
movies _ ``If they do `God IV' I'll be glad to come down again'' _
and says since he's a senior citizen he can see himself for half
price.
   Hope, according to the Guinness Book of Records the most
decorated man in show business, opened the show, for 50 minutes.
Then Dionne Warwick sang, making a dynamic ``I'll Never Love This
Way Again'' the high point of her set.
   ``I'm not an opening act you know,'' Hope said. Adding that he
was glad to open for Burns, Hope said, ``If they ever have a Mount
Rushmore of comedians, this man has to be the first man on that
mountain.''
   Hope said he hadn't played New York since 1968 when he and Bing
Crosby put on the show that opened Madison Square Garden. That time
the stage also was in the center of the floor but it was rigged as
a boxing ring and Hope ``fought'' Rocky Marciano.
   This time, all Hope had to contend with was a comedian who could
one up him.
   He made his show business debut at 8 in New York, Burns said.
``They must have liked me. Here it is 85 years later and I'm back
again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
