<DOCNO> AP891001-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1338EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MoneySearch Bjt   10-01 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Search, Bjt,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Puts Money And Ideas Into One Room</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stakes are high and pockets deep at an annual
venture capital conference, where aspiring entrepreneurs try to
persuade investors to risk millions on business ideas ranging from
lightweight planes to submarine tours.
   ``We're real excited after our research,'' said Nancy Young,
who's looking for $3.8 million to buy a submarine and take tourists
for an underwater look at the Caribbean. ``We have found the
concept to be more interesting and profitable than when we first
conceived it a year ago.''
   She is hoping to follow such firms as Hospitality Network Ltd.,
which got $8.3 million in cash and credit two years ago. The
company has multiplied 10 times in value since then, founder Chris
Tyson said.
   Then there's Bookstop Inc., which got $3.5 million three years
ago when it was a five-store, money-losing chain.
   Last week, New York-based BDB Corp., parent of B. Dalton
Bookseller and Barnes &amp; Noble, paid a reported $10 million to buy
controlling interest in the company, which now operates 22 stores
in four states.
   ``Bookstop is on its way to doing the kind of fantastic things
that we all talk about,'' said Jerry White, director of Southern
Methodist University's Caruth Institute of Owner-Managed Business,
which is sponsoring the Southwest Venture Capital Conference in
Dallas.
   ``Basically what we do is give people a 10-minute opportunity.
Whether they pull it off is in their ball park,'' White said.
   ``Many of these (venture capital) firms you would have
difficulty getting an appointment with,'' White said, estimating it
would take a year and $100,000 of travel to get access to the same
investors.
   ``Getting past the secretary is going to be a major ordeal and
getting your story told is going to be another ordeal,'' he said.
``If you compete (in the conference) and win a spot you'll get your
story out to the industry.''
   This is the seventh conference the institute has sponsored along
with newly merged accountants Ernst &amp; Young and a Dallas law firm.
White estimates investors have provided $100 million to growing
businesses either directly from the conference or through contacts
made as a result of the meeting.
   The conference gave Tyson the opportunity he had been unable to
get elsewhere as he searched for investors in his Austin-based
Hospitality Network, which provides cable television service to the
hotel industry.
   ``On a wild hair I decided to submit a business plan to the
conference because I knew I would get in front of a bunch of
folks,'' Tyson said. ``I spoke, gave a little slide show on where
this company would go (and) we had 'em lining up at the door.''
   More than 150 business plans are submitted annually to the
conference. The plans are valuated and the 20 or so deemed to have
the best ideas are then given time in front of the potential
investors.
   ``The only people in the room are the presenters and the
investors,'' White said. Then the companies are given a room at one
of Dallas' upscale hotels where they wait to see if any interested
investors come by.
   There's a ``second 20,'' White said, who don't get time, but
have their plans forwarded to the investors. The remaining never
make it to the investors.
   That screening is what has made the conference popular with
venture capitalists, White said.
   ``If a venture capitalist can have a competitive committee of
people that screens 150 deals down to the best 20 and presents them
in a time-efficient process, we feel that's a very efficient mode
of looking for deals on behalf of the venture capitalist,'' he said.
   About 150 venture capital funds pay $150 each to attend the
conference; presenters, who are usually from the Southwest, pay
$500. This year's two-day conference starts Monday.
   White said many of the plans chosen are technology-driven,
reflecting investors' bias in that area, and generally are firms
that have been in business for some time and an experienced
management already in place.
   This year's finalists include eight high-tech firms that sell
software and other computer-related products. Others include a
company that designs, makes and markets solar collector products; a
manufacturer of low-cost, lightweight aircraft; and Young
Enterprises' idea for sub tours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
