<FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1401EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TaiwanEmpire Bjt   10-01 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan Empire, Bjt,0892</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan's Nationalist Government Selling Off Part of Business Empire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-KMT Empire on AM-Business News Digest. Also moved
in advance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The immense business empire of the
Nationalist government, long a key element in the control of
Taiwan, is under attack and plans are being made to begin its sale.
   Now that the people of Taiwan have won some say in this island's
political process, they are demanding a larger share of the
economic pie. The government has reacted by promising to sell off
some of its numerous firms.
   But critics say the government and party aren't going far enough
and that Taiwan's rulers will maintain control of the financial
empire through joint ventures, stock schemes and other roundabout
ways.
   About half of all the total assets of Taiwan's companies are
controlled directly or indirectly by the ruling Nationalist Party
or the government. The net worth of these assets is more than $380
billion, according to Kang Ning-hsiang, a legislator of the
fledgling opposition Democratic Progressive Party who has
researched the holdings.
   Together the party and government dominate Taiwan's petroleum
industry; telecommunication systems; railways; steel, cement and
shipbuilding plants; and parts of the mass media.
   The government also owns 70 percent of Taiwan's 9 million acres
of land and maintains a firm grip on the economy through its
control of foreign exchange and the banking system.
   ``From gasoline for cars to raw materials for the clothes we
wear, everything is more or less under the Nationalist control,''
said Kang.
   Inhabitants on this island of 20 million, already among the most
densely populated in the world, have to fight ``the most severe
battle'' for the limited resources open to the public, said Kang.
   The Nationalists and as many as 2 million followers fled to
Taiwan in 1949 following their loss in a civil war to the Communist
forces in China. Since then the party and the state have been
inseparable. The Democratic Progressive Party, a legal entity since
1987, has yet to come close to challenging Nationalist supremacy.
   In Taiwan, economic interests have been the foundation of
Nationalist rule. Through them the party dispenses favors to
loyalists and privileges to cooperative private businesses.
   In the beginning, the favors went mostly to the mainlanders who
fled with the Nationalists. But as local Taiwanese slowly began to
assert themselves both economically and politically, the
Nationalists attempted to attract them with favors, too.
   Pressure on the party and government to turn state- and
party-run firms private increased after Taiwan lifted martial law
in 1987, paving the way for the current political liberalization.
   A prosperous economy added more pressure, creating an abundance
of idle cash looking for investment opportunities.
   In August, the government announced that 19 of Taiwan's 59
state-run firms will either go public or be sold to private
enterprises under a program that may take many years to complete.
   Among the firms to be made private are several banks, insurance
companies, chemical firms, steel mills and a shipbuilder. Many of
the concerns have lost money and drained government finances
despite their total or near monopolies.
   But the government will retain the bulk of its holdings, such as
the lucrative Chinese Petroleum Corp., which monopolizes oil
imports, exploration, refinery, gasoline stations and several
petrochemical products.
   ``The Nationalists will see to it that they will not lose much
of their economic or political influence'' with the conversion to
private companies, said Chu Yun-han, professor of political science
at the National Taiwan University.
   The government is expected to hold minority shares in the
companies it sells, thereby allowing the Nationalist Party
continued influence, Chu said.
   The party will continue to appoint retired officials as key
executives at the companies and secure the ``iron ballots'' of
employees in elections, he said.
   Despite the government's program to sell public companies,
Nationalist Party officials said they had no similar plans to
reduce the giant party-owned business empire.
   The party network of about 50 companies includes one that
finances all stock purchases for Taiwan's stock market.
   The party also owns a television station, a radio station and a
newspaper, constituting a powerful propaganda tool.
   Lawmakers from the Democratic Progressive Party have vowed to
end what they claim is ``the flow from national coffers to party
coffers.'' But most efforts have failed because of the complexity
of these businesses, many of which are joint ventures with private
businesses.
   The government decided this year to cut its annual subsidy of $9
million to the party's Broadcasting Corp. of China by 10 percent
each year for three consecutive years.
   Opposition activists accuse the Nationalists of funneling money
from their businesses into the campaign coffers of ruling party
politicians. The prestigious Journalist weekly said ruling
party-owned companies and other state sources contribute an
estimated $75 million to campaign funds in each national election.
   Political observers say exclusive government contracts or
monopolies of party-owned businesses eventually will have to end,
forcing some companies to close.
   But the road will be rocky.
   ``Most of the new benefits will go to the vested interests,''
says legislator Kang. ``True liberalization has a long way to go.''
</TEXT>
