<FIRST>r f AM-Braniff     10-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Braniff,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Braniff Plans 47 Flights Monday From 11 Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc., which grounded nearly all its
256 daily flights last week after entering federal bankruptcy court
proceedings, said Sunday it would offer 47 flights on Monday.
   The airline offered seats on the flights at $49 each, one-way
from 11 cities. The fare applies to flights between any two cities
in the system, but all flights will go through either Braniff's
Kansas City, Mo., hub or Orlando.
   Braniff increased service from four flights Thursday, when it
filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors in federal
bankrupcty court in Orlando, to eight daily departures Saturday and
Sunday.
   ``We believe the routes we are operating with these highly
competitive fares will provide a solid foundation for further
expansion,'' Tom Volz, senior vice president for marketing, said in
a statement.
   The $49 one-way fares will be offered through Thursday, Braniff
said. The airline then will offer $99 one-way fares for the rest of
October.
   The Monday flights will serve Orlando; Kansas City; Los Angeles;
San Francisco; San Diego; Chicago; Newark, N.J.; Washington, D.C.,
National Airport; La Guardia Airport in New York; Dallas and
Phoenix.
   Before Wednesday, the airline operated 55 jets and flew to 39
U.S. cities and Nassau, the Bahamas.
   Braniff spokesman Don McGuire said discount fares appear to be
attracting travelers. As of Saturday afternoon, about half the
seats on some flights had been reserved for the reduced fare
flights.
</TEXT>
